            .

Columns 1–3 of the table correspond to the comparison between the joint profits of the merged entity before and after the merger (
               \documentclass{aastex} \usepackage{amsbsy} \usepackage{amsfonts} \usepackage{amssymb} \usepackage{bm} \usepackage{mathrsfs} \usepackage{pifont} \usepackage{stmaryrd} \usepackage{textcomp} \usepackage{portland,xspace} \usepackage{amsmath,amsxtra} \usepackage[OT2,OT1]{fontenc} \newcommand\cyr{ \renewcommand\rmdefault{wncyr} \renewcommand\sfdefault{wncyss} \renewcommand\encodingdefault{OT2} \normalfont \selectfont} \DeclareTextFontCommand{\textcyr}{\cyr} \pagestyle{empty} \DeclareMathSizes{10}{9}{7}{6} \begin{document} \landscape $2C^{*}$ \end{document}
            and
               \documentclass{aastex} \usepackage{amsbsy} \usepackage{amsfonts} \usepackage{amssymb} \usepackage{bm} \usepackage{mathrsfs} \usepackage{pifont} \usepackage{stmaryrd} \usepackage{textcomp} \usepackage{portland,xspace} \usepackage{amsmath,amsxtra} \usepackage[OT2,OT1]{fontenc} \newcommand\cyr{ \renewcommand\rmdefault{wncyr} \renewcommand\sfdefault{wncyss} \renewcommand\encodingdefault{OT2} \normalfont \selectfont} \DeclareTextFontCommand{\textcyr}{\cyr} \pagestyle{empty} \DeclareMathSizes{10}{9}{7}{6} \begin{document} \landscape $C_{m}$ \end{document}
            , respectively). Columns 4–8 reflect the extent of variability in the levels of advertising of different stations. Column 4 is the advertising level of each of the merging partners
               \documentclass{aastex} \usepackage{amsbsy} \usepackage{amsfonts} \usepackage{amssymb} \usepackage{bm} \usepackage{mathrsfs} \usepackage{pifont} \usepackage{stmaryrd} \usepackage{textcomp} \usepackage{portland,xspace} \usepackage{amsmath,amsxtra} \usepackage[OT2,OT1]{fontenc} \newcommand\cyr{ \renewcommand\rmdefault{wncyr} \renewcommand\sfdefault{wncyss} \renewcommand\encodingdefault{OT2} \normalfont \selectfont} \DeclareTextFontCommand{\textcyr}{\cyr} \pagestyle{empty} \DeclareMathSizes{10}{9}{7}{6} \begin{document} \landscape $\overline{\varphi }^{0}$ \end{document}
            , column 5 is the advertising levels of the station that is located the farthest away from the merged entity
               \documentclass{aastex} \usepackage{amsbsy} \usepackage{amsfonts} \usepackage{amssymb} \usepackage{bm} \usepackage{mathrsfs} \usepackage{pifont} \usepackage{stmaryrd} \usepackage{textcomp} \usepackage{portland,xspace} \usepackage{amsmath,amsxtra} \usepackage[OT2,OT1]{fontenc} \newcommand\cyr{ \renewcommand\rmdefault{wncyr} \renewcommand\sfdefault{wncyss} \renewcommand\encodingdefault{OT2} \normalfont \selectfont} \DeclareTextFontCommand{\textcyr}{\cyr} \pagestyle{empty} \DeclareMathSizes{10}{9}{7}{6} \begin{document} \landscape $\overline{\varphi }^{( n/ 2) -1}$ \end{document}
            , column 6 is the average level of advertising of all stations, and column 7 is a measure of the extent of asymmetry in the levels of advertising of the stations.20The calculations in the table indicate that a merger between two stations is more likely to enhance their joint payoff the larger the number of competing stations (largen), the smaller the degree of differentiation between stations, and the more annoyed consumers are by advertising (large values of
               \documentclass{aastex} \usepackage{amsbsy} \usepackage{amsfonts} \usepackage{amssymb} \usepackage{bm} \usepackage{mathrsfs} \usepackage{pifont} \usepackage{stmaryrd} \usepackage{textcomp} \usepackage{portland,xspace} \usepackage{amsmath,amsxtra} \usepackage[OT2,OT1]{fontenc} \newcommand\cyr{ \renewcommand\rmdefault{wncyr} \renewcommand\sfdefault{wncyss} \renewcommand\encodingdefault{OT2} \normalfont \selectfont} \DeclareTextFontCommand{\textcyr}{\cyr} \pagestyle{empty} \DeclareMathSizes{10}{9}{7}{6} \begin{document} \landscape $h\equiv \gamma / t_{s}$ \end{document}
            ). Column 8 of the table explains this result. When the media market is highly competitive, the extent of asymmetry in the levels of advertising of the different stations as measured by the relative range calculation is larger. Recall from our earlier explanation that it is this asymmetry among stations that can reverse the negative consequences of the merger on the producer surplus generated in the product market. Note also that a merger is less likely to be profitable, the higher the selected premerger levels of advertising (smalln, big
               \documentclass{aastex} \usepackage{amsbsy} \usepackage{amsfonts} \usepackage{amssymb} \usepackage{bm} \usepackage{mathrsfs} \usepackage{pifont} \usepackage{stmaryrd} \usepackage{textcomp} \usepackage{portland,xspace} \usepackage{amsmath,amsxtra} \usepackage[OT2,OT1]{fontenc} \newcommand\cyr{ \renewcommand\rmdefault{wncyr} \renewcommand\sfdefault{wncyss} \renewcommand\encodingdefault{OT2} \normalfont \selectfont} \DeclareTextFontCommand{\textcyr}{\cyr} \pagestyle{empty} \DeclareMathSizes{10}{9}{7}{6} \begin{document} \landscape $t_{s}$ \end{document}
            , small γ, and large η). Hence, if producers advertise intensely, even in the absence of a merger, the further increase in their advertising levels as a result of the merger implies that the latter is unambiguously unprofitable.

The results expressed intable 1for the specific example
               \documentclass{aastex} \usepackage{amsbsy} \usepackage{amsfonts} \usepackage{amssymb} \usepackage{bm} \usepackage{mathrsfs} \usepackage{pifont} \usepackage{stmaryrd} \usepackage{textcomp} \usepackage{portland,xspace} \usepackage{amsmath,amsxtra} \usepackage[OT2,OT1]{fontenc} \newcommand\cyr{ \renewcommand\rmdefault{wncyr} \renewcommand\sfdefault{wncyss} \renewcommand\encodingdefault{OT2} \normalfont \selectfont} \DeclareTextFontCommand{\textcyr}{\cyr} \pagestyle{empty} \DeclareMathSizes{10}{9}{7}{6} \begin{document} \landscape $G( \varphi ) =\varphi ^{\eta }$ \end{document}
            tend to contradict, as before, the implications of horizontal mergers in regular product markets. In a differentiated oligopoly model in which producers compete in prices, a nonconsolidated merger of two neighboring producers is unambiguously beneficial to the merging parties. Moreover, the benefit from the merger is larger, both in absolute and relative terms, the less competitive the product market is (seeApp. B). The latter result is the exact opposite of the comparative statics derived intable 1for a nonconsolidated merger in media markets. The reason for the different results stems from the role the media market plays in informing consumers about the brands available in product markets, and the fact that such information induces intensified price competition among brands.

In view of the results reported in proposition 5, we can now predict the equilibria of the entire game. Specifically, if the media market consists of only two stations, they will never find it profitable to merge in the first stage of the game. With a larger number of participants in the media market, two neighboring stations may find it advantageous to merge only if the media market is highly competitive or if the nuisance parameter γ is sufficiently big (for the specific example). A merger between two nonneighboring stations is an equilibrium since the merging parties are indifferent between merging or not merging. If the merger introduces additional synergies in the form of cost reductions, for instance (i.e.,
               \documentclass{aastex} \usepackage{amsbsy} \usepackage{amsfonts} \usepackage{amssymb} \usepackage{bm} \usepackage{mathrsfs} \usepackage{pifont} \usepackage{stmaryrd} \usepackage{textcomp} \usepackage{portland,xspace} \usepackage{amsmath,amsxtra} \usepackage[OT2,OT1]{fontenc} \newcommand\cyr{ \renewcommand\rmdefault{wncyr} \renewcommand\sfdefault{wncyss} \renewcommand\encodingdefault{OT2} \normalfont \selectfont} \DeclareTextFontCommand{\textcyr}{\cyr} \pagestyle{empty} \DeclareMathSizes{10}{9}{7}{6} \begin{document} \landscape $f_{sm}< 2f_{s}$ \end{document}
            ), then a merger between two nonneighbors may actually dominate a merger between two neighbors. For the specific example we have considered, two nonneighbors will merge in the first stage in order to take advantage of synergies if the media market is highly concentrated and the degree of differentiation among stations is large.

